Certainly! Below is an example of how to generate an automatically updated table of contents in a LaTeX document. This example includes the necessary commands to ensure the table of contents is generated automatically.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{hyperref} % For hyperlinks in the table of contents

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Background}
This section provides the background information.

\section{Methodology}
This section discusses the methodology used in the research.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results obtained from the research.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Document Class and Package**: The `\documentclass{article}` command specifies the type of document (in this case, an article). The `\usepackage{hyperref}` command is used to enable hyperlinks in the table of contents, making it more useful if you click on a section title in the PDF.

2. **Table of Contents**: The `\tableofcontents` command is placed in the document to generate the table of contents. LaTeX automatically lists all the sections and subsections defined in the document up to this point.

3. **Sections and Contents**: Each `\section{...}` command defines a new section in the document. The text within the curly braces becomes the section title. When the `\tableofcontents` command is executed, these titles are listed in the table of contents.

4. **Document End**: The `\end{document}` command signifies the end of the document.

This simple example demonstrates how LaTeX automatically generates a table of contents based on the sections defined in the document. The `hyperref` package is optional but beneficial for creating clickable links in the table of contents, enhancing the navigability of the document.

To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LATEX, you can use the `chessboard` package, which provides an easy way to draw chessboards. Here is an example of how you can create a LATEX code that includes all the required commands and packages to draw a chessboard from a FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{xfp}

% Define a function to convert a FEN notation to a LATEX code for the chessboard
\newcommand{\fenboard}[1]{%
  \chessboard[
    setfen={#1},
    showmover=false,
    color=white,
    linewidth=1pt,
    showmover=false
  ]
}

\begin{document}

% Example FEN notation
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

\end{document}
```

In this code, we use the `chessboard` package to draw the chessboard. The `setfen` option takes the FEN notation as its argument, and the `showmover` option is set to `false` to hide the mover indicator.

You can replace the example FEN notation with your own FEN notation to draw a different chessboard.

